metadata.name: Schetsboek  #9
metadata.description:
This is my little tribute to fx (hash and fam).

During an important phone call, I was put on hold. Unconsciously, I began to scribble in my sketchbook. Research shows that scribbling helps focusing, but I dreamed away nonetheless until my pages were filled with scribbles, notes, shopping and a to-do list. 

Mint a uniquely generated page from my non-existent 100% coded sketchbook (except text typography). 

The page may contain many scribbles and drawings in pen, felt-tip pen, pencil, or less: often references to artists I admire, some in the form of loose scribbles, others in the form of riddles. Those drawings are drawn with code and vary. Unfortunately, I wasnâ€™t able to incorporate tributes to all art and every artist I admire. The sketchbook would never finish. Thanks to rudxane I know that itâ€™s ok to publish something unfinished ;-). 

One reference that appears in every token is to Sol Lewitt, an incredible source of inspiration. His artworks consist of instructions. Your sketch book pages contain instructions too. You will find the instructions for the artwork scribbled on your unique page by pressing i.

Curious how the work would look without the â€˜distractingâ€™ scribbles and coffee stains? Press â€˜aâ€™, â€˜wâ€™, or â€˜gâ€™. 

800 x 800 px

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save an image.

Made with p5js and the amazing p5.scribble.js library by Janneck Wullschleger.

Font used: Sacremento-Regular under the SIL Open Font License (OFL).

See license.md for the licenses of both.

Thank you all!

metadata.name: Klimtiche #39
metadata.description:
Inspired by the 'Tree of Life' by Gustav Klimt.
Every bird comes with a default weather setting but all weather is optional.
On the keyboard:
use 's' to make it snow
use 'w' to make wind blow
use 'r' to make it rain
use 'n' to stop the animation and then again to clear all animation. 
Variables are snow intensity, rain intensity, wind speed and palette.
Made in p5.js, every tree / meadow / sky is unique in design.
Two birds is rare.
Monochrome is rare.

metadata.name: Solace #224
metadata.description:
Solace is an algorithm that generates artworks of sand dunes. It draws hundreds of thousands of tiny points according to a probability distribution calculated from the positions of the dunes.

The logic to divide the dunes into light and dark sides is simple, but produces some interesting chaotic behaviour. These are details that weren't hard-coded but emerge organically, such as the patterns on the spines of the dunes or the stripes around their bases.

Please note that the algorithm can take some time to run, especially when the number of dunes is high.

Created by lunarean.

metadata.name: Sprocket Factory #251
metadata.description:
Just an ordinary scene from a typical day, working as a Sprocket Factory engineer. Inspiration for this work is drawn from the composable nature of blockchain smart contracts and the flow of value between networks of autonomous machines and free-willed individuals.

"A Doodle, Ringer, and Fidenza walk into a Space Bar..."

- Live renderer best viewed in Chrome.
- Press "P" to export an PNG raster image (10k resolution.)
- Press "S" to export an SVG vector.

metadata.name: Euphonic #1194
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the MoirÃ© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Vorticity #86
metadata.description:
Vorticity is a gpu-accelerated flow field. The particles in the flow field orbit around a set of points that move around over time.

Controls: Click and drag to push particles away. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation a single step. Press "r" to restart the simulation (if you change the resolution of the screen after the page loads, you will need to restart to update the resolution).

metadata.name: MetaMountains #10
metadata.description:
Beautiful MetaMountains to stare and escape from reality, sometimes they will look like any other mountain, and Sometimes while you look at them you will have the feeling of seeing the terrain of a planet in a distant galaxy.

Is that a regular mountain? No! It's a MetaMountain! You may even witness the rise of two suns or two moons.

No fancy features, just waves, and shapes with 8 hand-picked color schemes. Sit back and enjoy.

----

[] Farm Mountains
[] Summer Mountains
[] Carbon Mountains
[] Arizona Mountains
[] Nordic Mountains

metadata.name: Little Trees #102
metadata.description:
Delicate, little trees. Some with green leaves, some with orange, some with red. This is the genesis project of Brian Gawlik.

The default resolution is 3600x3600. To redraw and save as an image at a different resolution - in the live view, open your browser's devtools and execute the function saveImg(pixWidth) where pixWidth is the desired width in pixels of the image. For example, saveImg(4096) will prompt you to download a 4096x4096 image. It is recommended not to export below 2400x2400 as this will compromise the aesthetic of the shadow.
